A chemical plant explosion in Jilin province, China, led to lethal chemicals entering the Songhua River, prompting environmental concerns.
The government allocated funds for pollution control and activated contingency plans to safeguard water quality.
China informed Russia of the pollution, emphasizing cooperation to address the issue.
Harbin, a city heavily reliant on the river for drinking water, took emergency measures to protect public safety.
Efforts to dilute pollutants included increased water discharge from hydropower stations.
China vowed to reduce emissions and prioritize pollution control in major rivers, including the Songhua.
